religion, and economic theory helped shape ideals and practices of masculinity. Kuchta allows us to see the process working in reverse, in that masculine manners and habits of consumption in a patriarchal society contributed actively to people's understanding of what held England together.Kuchta shows not only how the ideology of modern English masculinity was a self-consciously political and public creation but also how such explicitly political decisions and values became internalized, personalized, and naturalized into everyday manners and habits.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMasculinityxHistory. 0aMen's clothingzEnglandxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  acapitalism.  acharacter.  achivalry.  aclothing.  aconsumption.  acostume history.  aearly modern england.  aenglish masculinity.  afashion and clothing.  afashion.  agender studies.  agender.  ahistory.  aking charles ii.  amanliness.  amasculine attire.  amasculine character.  amasculine manners.  amasculine.  amasculinity.  amens fashion.  amenswear.  amodern england.  amonarchy.  amoral authority.  anonfiction.  apatriarchy.  apublic character.  apublic man.  areputation.  aself fashioning.  aself made man.  asuccess.  asuit.  athree piece suit.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021493440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092139940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520921399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520921399/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY